description: Borrowed from Middle French ceder, from Old French ceder, from Latin cēdō (“to yield”), from Proto-Indo-European *ḱyesdʰ- (“to drive away; to go away”). Cognate with Tocharian B kätk- (“to cross, pass”).

verbs.description: cede (third-person singular simple present cedes, present participle ceding, simple past and past participle ceded)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To give up; yield to another.
examples: Edward decided to cede the province.
